text.tspan: State Population Change 1790-2000

g.text: Data obtained from US Bureau of Census records, 2001

svg.text: Created by R. K. Wright, Adobe Systems, 2001

text.tspan: This graph shows the relative population of the selected state. The
blue
line is the proportion of the state's population relative to the
maximum population of that state over the past 210 years. The
red
line is the proportion of the total US population for the state,
scaled by the maximum value it has ever reached.
In most cases, states have grown more or less steadily, but some
states have actually shrunk (
e.g.
North Dakota and West Virginia
as can be seen from the blue (population) curve.
The red (proportion)
curve is most interesting because it shows the
trends
in the state's populations. Notice, for example, the growth
of Georgia - it is rapid early in the 19th century with the rise of the
slave trade, then declines after the civil war only to rise again
recently with the growth of Atlanta and the tech industry in the
southeastern US. The silver boom in Nevada and the gold rush in
North Dakota can both be seen. The land rush into what is now
Oklahoma at the turn of the 20th century is very
striking.
